iple, Heron contends, is liturgy—understood in the broad sense as “public service.” Whereas until now only liturgy’s acclamatory dimension has made the concept available for political theory, Heron positions it more broadly as a technique of governance. What Christianity has bequeathed to political thought and forms, he argues, is thus a paradoxical technology of power that is grounded uniquely in service.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChristianity and politics. 0aChurch and state. 0aPolitical theology. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aPolitical Science. 4aReligion. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aCarl Schmitt.  aChristianity.  aGiorgio Agamben.  aPolitical Theology.  agovernmentality.  ahierarchy.  aliturgy.  apolitics.  apower.  asecularization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823278718zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823278718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823278718/original  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK